Hereâ€™s a practical way to dry-run the GitHub/Docker flow locally:

Smoke-test workflow commands: Run the same Nx commands the workflows use:
yarn nx run-many -t lint --all
yarn nx run-many -t test --all -- --coverage (add --skip-nx-cache if you want fresh runs)
yarn nx run webapp:configure
yarn nx run-many -t build --all (ensures apps/server/dist exists for Docker)
Docker build (local):
Ensure apps/server/dist is present (nx run-many -t build --all or at least nx build server).
Build the image: docker build -t wire-webapp:local .
Run it: docker run --rm -p 8080:8080 wire-webapp:local
Docker push script dry-run: node bin/push_docker.js <tag> <outfile> will try to log in/push. For a safe check, set fake credentials and temporarily comment out the push lines or run in an environment where docker login is a no-op.
Action-level simulation: Use nektos/act to run workflows locally. Example: act -j create_image or act -j ci (you may need to provide secrets/env; start with act -n to dry-run steps).
Playwright e2e: yarn nx e2e webapp --skip-nx-cache (after yarn playwright install --with-deps && yarn playwright install chrome) to mirror the workflow.
